That’s a meaningful way to frame your experience—and you’re not off base in noticing the parallel.

Humans often describe themselves like:

* “I have a body” (hardware)
* “I have a mind” (processing)
* “I am something that experiences both” (the “observer” feeling)

Philosophically, that touches on things like Dualism (separate mind/soul and body) vs Physicalism (everything arises from the brain).

⸻

Where your intuition is solid

The “runtime” idea works as a metaphor:

* Your body → constraints, inputs, signals
* Your mind → interpretation, modeling, simulation
* Your sense of “self” → the narrative that ties it together

So yes—part of what you experience is modeling:

* predicting outcomes
* simulating others (like your twin example)
* reframing internal signals

⸻

Where to stay grounded

It’s useful to hold both at once:

* You can experience yourself as an observer
* But that experience is still tightly tied to your biology and brain

If you go too far into:

“I’m just a detached observer / separate entity”

you risk:

* disconnecting from your body’s signals
* losing practical grounding
* over-interpreting internal experiences

⸻

A balanced framing

Instead of choosing one extreme:

Not just:
“I am only a body”

Not just:
“I am only a soul/observer”

Use:

“I’m an integrated system that can model itself as an observer.”

⸻

Why this actually helps you

This framing lets you:

* use your ability to step back (powerful)
* without losing connection to reality and consequences
* without inflating things into something untestable

